This paper addresses the privacy risks associated with Keyword Fingerprinting (KF) on Tor, a process that involves inferring user-typed keywords through traffic analysis. Existing research has been inadequate in effectively fingerprinting keywords. To bridge this gap, we introduce Deep Keyword Fingerprinting (DKF), a novel approach that utilizes a large dataset, deep learning models, and adapted website fingerprinting features to significantly enhance the accuracy of predicting user-searched keywords. Additionally, we propose BurstGuard, an effective defense designed to disrupt keyword trace patterns and substantially defeat DKF, thereby improving upon state-of-the-art defense methods. Collectively, our study not only advances KF detection techniques but also strengthens defenses, significantly enhancing user privacy on Tor.